Voter Turnout in 2016 and 2020¶

Introduction¶

In this short article we're going to examine voting patterns in Michigan in the 2016 and 2020 elections. Specifically, we are going to investigate whether improved voter turnout in 2020 compared to 2016 favored Joe Biden or Donald Trump.

The data we will use for the analysis are available at 2016 and 2020. Note that despite the filetypes indicated by the file extensions these are tab-separated text files, and not actual Excel files.

The question we are interested in answering here is: was the change in voter turnout for Democrats and Republicans from 2016 to 2020 the same?

Data Cleaning and Preprocessing¶

First, we pre-process the data from the 2016 and 2020 elections. We're going to relabel missing data as "missing" so that we can use filtration and reduction functions on this data. We will also relabel missing numerical data as 0 (so, if the number of votes reported for a given candidate is missing it will be treated as 0) for similar reasons. We recode the OfficeDescription column for ease of use.

In [9]:
election2016 = CSV.read("2016GEN_MI_CENR_BY_COUNTY.xls",delim="\t",DataFrame)
election2016[ismissing.(election2016.OfficeDescription),:OfficeDescription] .= "missing"
election2016[ismissing.(election2016.CandidateLastName),:CandidateLastName] .= "missing"
election2016[election2016.OfficeDescription .== "President of the United States 4 Year Term (1) Position",:OfficeDescription] .= "president"
election2016[ismissing.(election2016.CandidateVotes),:CandidateVotes] .= 0

election2020 = CSV.read("2020GEN_MI_CENR_BY_COUNTY.xls",delim="\t",DataFrame)
election2020[ismissing.(election2020.OfficeDescription),:OfficeDescription] .= "missing"
election2020[ismissing.(election2020.CandidateLastName),:CandidateLastName] .= "missing"
election2020[election2020.OfficeDescription .== "President of the United States 4 Year Term (1) Position",:OfficeDescription] .= "president"
election2020[ismissing.(election2020.CandidateVotes),:CandidateVotes] .= 0

Now, we're going to get the county-level voter turnout data for Republican and Democratic candidates in each election

In [15]:
clinton_votes = @> election2016 begin
    @where(:CandidateLastName .== "Clinton", :OfficeDescription .== "president")
    @select(:CountyName,ClintonVotes = :CandidateVotes)
end

democrat_votes = @> election2020 begin
    @where(:CandidateLastName .== "Biden", :OfficeDescription .== "president")
    @select(:CountyName,BidenVotes = :CandidateVotes)
    leftjoin(clinton_votes, on = :CountyName)
    @transform(Diff = :BidenVotes .- :ClintonVotes)
end

trump_votes = @> election2016 begin
    @where(:CandidateLastName .== "Trump", :OfficeDescription .== "president")
    @select(:CountyName,TrumpVotes16 = :CandidateVotes)
end

republican_votes = @> election2020 begin
    @where(:CandidateLastName .== "Trump", :OfficeDescription .== "president")
    @select(:CountyName,TrumpVotes20 = :CandidateVotes)
    leftjoin(trump_votes, on = :CountyName)
    @transform(Diff = :TrumpVotes20 .- :TrumpVotes16)
end

Analysis¶

Let's start by looking at the average difference in voters for 2016 vs 2020 for Democrats and Republicans.

In [18]:
(mean_diff_dem, mean_diff_rep) = (mean(democrat_votes.Diff), mean(republican_votes.Diff))
Out[18]:
(6448.204819277108, 4461.55421686747)

On average, Biden saw almost 6500 more voters per county over Clinton, whereas Trump only saw an average of 4500 voters more in 2020 than in 2016. What does this mean to us? To investigate that, let's first look at the histograms of the differences and see if that tells us anything about the distributions.

In [28]:
Plots.histogram(democrat_votes.Diff, color=:blue, label="Democrats", xformatter=:plain)
Plots.histogram!(republican_votes.Diff, color=:red, label="Republicans")
Out[28]:

The two big things we notice here are that neither of these distributions are normal, and the distribution for Democrats has a much longer tail than that for Republicans. We also note that no counties had a negative change in voter turnout (i.e. every county saw turnout either the same or greater in 2020 vs 2016). Let's use non-parametric methods to take a deeper look into the differences between these two distributions.

In [30]:
ecdfdem = ecdf(democrat_votes.Diff)
ecdfrep = ecdf(republican_votes.Diff)
Plots.scatter(democrat_votes.Diff,ecdfdem(democrat_votes.Diff),label="Democrat",legend=:bottomright,color=:blue,xformatter=:plain)
Plots.scatter!(republican_votes.Diff,ecdfrep(republican_votes.Diff),label="Republican",color=:red)
Plots.xlabel!("Turnout Change")
Plots.ylabel!("Cumulative percentage")
Out[30]:

We can see from this graph that at the lower turnout changes the Republicans are to the right of the graph for the Democrats, but at some point the two graphs cross and the Democrats have a few counties with much higher turnout changes than any county had for the Republican party. This is similar to the data we could glean from the histogram above.

Next we would like to use bootstrap permutation sampling to see if there's a statistically significant difference between the two distributions.

In [32]:
function permutation_sample(data1, data2)
    data = vcat(data1,data2)
    p = Random.randperm(length(data))
    permuted_data = data[p]
    perm_sample_1 = permuted_data[1:length(data1)]
    perm_sample_2 = permuted_data[length(data1)+1:end]
    perm_sample_1, perm_sample_2
end

function draw_perm_reps(data_1, data_2, func, sz=1)
    [func(permutation_sample(data_1,data_2)...) for i in 1:sz]
end

Plots.scatter(democrat_votes.Diff,ecdfdem(democrat_votes.Diff),label="Democrat",legend=:bottomright,color=:blue,xformatter=:plain)
Plots.scatter!(republican_votes.Diff,ecdfrep(republican_votes.Diff),label="Republican",color=:red)
for i in 1:50
    # Generate permutation samples
    sample_1, sample_2 = permutation_sample(democrat_votes.Diff,republican_votes.Diff)
    # Compute ECDFs
    x1, y1 = sample_1, ecdf(sample_1)(sample_1)
    x2, y2 = sample_2, ecdf(sample_2)(sample_2)
    # Plot ECDFs of permutation sample
    Plots.scatter!(x1,y1,color=:red,alpha=0.02,markersize=2,label=:none)
    Plots.scatter!(x2,y2,color=:blue,alpha=0.02,markersize=2,label=:none)
end
Plots.xlabel!("County vote percentages")
Plots.ylabel!("Cumulative percentage")
Out[32]:

The purple region in the middle of the graph shows us the kinds of samples we could expect if we make the assumption that the two elections were draws from the same pool of vote percentages. The fact that this region overlaps both distributions, which makes sense given the fact that they cross, leads us to believe that we are unlikely to see a statistically significant difference in voter turnout between the two parties. How confidant should we be about this result? We can compute the p-value by taking a large number of bootstrap samples and looking at how often the simulated difference in mean is less than or equal to (more extreme than) the observed difference in means of around 2000 that we calculated above.

In [34]:
function diff_of_means(data_1,data_2)
    mean(data_1) - mean(data_2)
end

empirical_diff_means = diff_of_means(democrat_votes.Diff,republican_votes.Diff)

bootstrap_reps = draw_perm_reps(democrat_votes.Diff,republican_votes.Diff,diff_of_means,100000)
p = sum(bootstrap_reps .>= empirical_diff_means) / length(bootstrap_reps)
println("p = $p")
println("The 95% confidence interval is ($(percentile(bootstrap_reps,2.5)),$(percentile(bootstrap_reps,97.5)))")

p = 0.14566
The 95% confidence interval is (-3513.8626506024093,3517.9343373493966)

Conclusion¶

A p-value of 0.144 indicates that we cannot reliably believe that the voter turnout differences for Republicans and Democrats had different underlying distributions. Since the 95% confidence interval contains 0, we cannot believe that the true difference in means is not 0. It also shows us that the range of credible outcomes for this election includes everything from an average of 3500 votes in favor of Trump to an average of 3500 votes in favor of Biden.
